div.p:
To gain a knowledge of the method, aim, necessity, etc., of Textual
Emendation the best books to read are:

Madvig Adversaria Critica, 3 vols., Copenhagen 1871-4 (emendations
of Latin and Greek authors);
Cobet Variae Lectiones, Leyden, 2nd ed., 1873 (emendations of Greek
authors);

The best photographic facsimiles are the costly
Palaeographical Society's Publications, London 1873 sqq. (Greek
and Latin);

The Greek word a)ni/an may be the cause of the corruption in Poen. 231,
postrémo modús muliebrís nullust núnquam;
lavándo et fricándo scimús facere a)ni/an, where the MSS. offer nníam and enjam.

The omission also of a syllable or a letter, though usually due to haplography (§ 3) or to the
confusion of one word with another of similar appearance,
e.g. filia for facilia (ch. v), or to the fact that the
syllable was expressed by a contraction symbol, e.g.
piratus for periratus (ch. vii. § 2), is occasionally
merely a case of illiterate copying. In Virg. A. iv. 491,

for example, MSS. offer descere for descendere;
in G. iii. 4 im for jam;
in G. iii. 154 arior for acrior;
in A. vi. 708 indunt for insidunt.

ab- and ad-, e.g. abduco and
adduco, Pseud. 1155, 1198;
aversus and adversus, Virg. G. i. 218.

tu and ut, freq., e.g. Mil. 1276;
and tum (freq.), tunc, e.g.
Pseud. 240, Merc. 552.

-m and -nt (see ch. vi. § 1), e.g. possum
for possunt, Lucr. i. 104;
cumulam for cumulant, Virg. A. xii. 515.

C, G, e.g. Bacch. 743 congregem for congraecem;
Asin. 632 delegit for dejecit;
Mil. 112 contegit for conjicit (conj&ebreve;cit); Amph. 285
furgifer (fugifer E) for furcifer. (For examples of the confusion
of c and g in A see Studemund's Index.)

E, F, e.g. Cas. 361 Eo dico for
Fodico, a corruption which may be later than the archetype in capitals, for the letter is the
initial letter of the line; Amph. 151 adest ferit for adeste erit;
Cas. 357 famus (fiamus J) for eamus;
Asin. 554 forum for eorum;
Asin. 555 eugae (euge EJ) for fugae;
Stich. 349 misera falgebunt (B: misera fulgebunt D)
for miserae algebunt.

(For examples in A see Studemund's Index, e.g. Epid. 226
eundis for fundis, Mil. 359 per fundum
for percundum.)

f, s (see above), e.g. Amph. 510 fustis
(E: furtis J) for si istis;
Cas. 404 sit for fit.

I, T, i, t (occasionally) e.g. Mil. 1066 vi for ut;
Pers. 285 vitu (B:
vita CD) for ut tu; Men. 988 utrum for
virum; Pseud. 1247 tacentem for jacentem;
Mil. 720 stet for si ci. (For examples in A see Studemund's Index.)

U with CI, TI, LI (see p. 87),
e.g. suam and sciam; aves and acies;
uvis and civis; ubi and tibi; parum and partim.

s (1) “sunt,” also st;
(2) “sive,” also siu, and occasionally su
(like the contraction of “sum”); (3) “sanctus”;
(4) “si”; (5) “sed.”

pro. Capital P with loop for ro has, I think, been mistaken
for capital D in Mil. 823:

prompsít nam nardini ámphoram cellárius.

animus ami “animi”;
Mil. 1068 (animi CD, edd., amicam B); cf.
Truc. 525 (anunt BCD for animum).

non n:  nam n Pseud. 521
nam for non (?); 642 non for nam;
Aul. 711 nam (ve)l non.

vel vl “vel”:
Mil. 1187 imponi velit (inponunt B, impono CD);
Truc. 246 vi ut for velut.

row.cell:
HEG. jam ego revertar intro, si ex his quae volo exquisivero

(am ego D, Nam ego F; que volo BDJ;
exquisi vero J).

nunc senex est in tostrina, nunc jam cultros adtinet

(bitostrina B1 DE V1, intostrina B2 V2, intonstrina J;
attinet VJ).

sed utrum strictimne adtonsurum dicam esse an per pectinem

(strictim ne B1DEVJ; attonsurum JF;
petinem B, first hand, DEV).
